content.text:
I have resolved the issue where complex card templates were broken in AnkiDroid due to `<script>` and `<style>` tags being stripped during media source parsing.

### Root Cause
The issue was located in the `parseSourcesToFileScheme` function within `TemplateManager.kt`. This function used `Jsoup.parse(content)` to parse the card's HTML content. Jsoup's default `parse` method assumes it is parsing a full HTML document and automatically moves any `<script>` or `<style>` tags found at the beginning of the content into the `<head>` element. However, the function subsequently returned only the contents of the `<body>` element (`doc.body().html()`), causing any tags moved to the `<head>` to be lost if any media source substitution (like updating an image path) occurred.

### Fix
I changed the parsing method to `Jsoup.parseBodyFragment(content)`. This method is specifically designed for parsing HTML fragments (which Anki templates are) and keeps `<script>` and `<style>` tags within the `<body>` unless they are explicitly wrapped in a `<head>` tag. This ensures that these tags are preserved when `doc.body().html()` is returned.

### Verification
- Created a reproduction test case with a mixed script and image template.
- Verified that the test failed before the fix (scripts were lost).
- Verified that the test passed after the fix (scripts were preserved and image sources were correctly updated).
- Verified that existing tests in `TemplateManagerTest.kt` still pass.
- Confirmed that `parseBodyFragment` correctly handles other tags like `<style>` and preserved them in the body.

```kotlin
// AnkiDroid/src/main/java/com/ichi2/libanki/TemplateManager.kt

fun parseSourcesToFileScheme(content: String, mediaDir: String): String {
    val doc = Jsoup.parseBodyFragment(content) // Changed from Jsoup.parse(content)
    doc.outputSettings(OutputSettings().prettyPrint(false))
    // ...
    return if (hasMadeChanges) {
        doc.body().html()
    } else {
        content
    }
}
```

